overview:
There are multiple assessment tools and treatment options available for the clinical management of fluency disorders. Students will learn theoretical constructs relative to the assessment and treatment of fluency disorders. While students will learn a number of assessment tools and treatment options, an exhaustive coverage of all assessments and treatments in fluency disorders is beyond the scope of this course. It is expected that students will further develop their knowledge within their clinical placements and across the duration of their professional careers. 

This course will: 
	Provide an overview of potential etiologies and characteristics of fluency disorders in children and adults; 
	Focus on assessment, diagnosis, and effective treatment of stuttering across the lifespan 
	Consider the experience of stuttering from the point of view of the person who stutters; 
	Emphasize the integration of normative data, scientific knowledge, and clinical practice.

Modeling of systems with emergent behavior. The course has two components: (1) basic and intermediate statistical mechanics, and (2) application of the course methods to a case study, chosen from topics to
include: dynamics of polymers, including proteins and nucleic acids; molecular machines; pattern formation, including turbulence and phyllotaxis; geomorphology; conflict including warfare, terrorism and revolution;
and economics.
